cosets, shown in red, green and blue. One can check that the cosets form a group of three elements (the product of a red element with a blue element is blue, the inverse of a blue element is green, etc.). Thus, the quotient group formula_25 is the group of three colors, which turns out to be the cyclic group with three elements.\nReal numbers modulo the integers.\nConsider the group of real numbers formula_99 under addition, and the subgroup formula_55 of integers. Each coset of formula_55 in formula_99 is a set of the form &amp;NoBreak;&amp;NoBreak;, where formula_31 is a real number. Since formula_104 and formula_105 are identical sets when the non-integer parts of formula_106 and formula_107 are equal, one may impose the restriction formula_108 without change of meaning. Adding such cosets is done by adding the corresponding real numbers, and subtracting 1 if the result is greater than or equal to 1. The quotient group formula_109 is isomorphic to the circle group, the group of complex numbers of absolute value 1 under multiplication, or correspondingly, the group of rotations in 2D about the origin, that is, the special orthogonal group &amp;NoBreak;&amp;NoBreak;. An isomorphism is given by formula_110 (see Euler's identity).\nMatrices of real numbers.\nIf formula_2 is the group of invertible formula_112 real matrices, and formula_3 is the subgroup of formula_112 real matrices with determinant 1, then formula_3 is normal in formula_2 (since it is the kernel of the determinant homomorphism). The cosets of formula_3 are the sets of matrices with a given determinant, and hence formula_25 is isomorphic to the multiplicative group of non-zero real numbers. The group formula_3 is known as the special linear group &amp;NoBreak;&amp;NoBreak;.\nInteger modular arithmetic.\nConsider the abelian group formula_120 (that is, the set formula_121 with addition modulo 4), and its subgroup &amp;NoBreak;}&amp;NoBreak;. The quotient group formula_122 is &amp;NoBreak;}&amp;NoBreak;