{"id": "11527", "revid": "38167511", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=11527", "title": "Fundamental theorem on homomorphisms", "text": "Theorem relating a group with the image and kernel of a homomorphism\nIn abstract algebra, the fundamental theorem on homomorphisms, also known as the fundamental homomorphism theorem, the first isomorphism theorem, or just the homomorphism theorem, relates the structure of two objects between which a homomorphism is given, and of the kernel and image of the homomorphism.\nThe homomorphism theorem is used to prove the isomorphism theorems. Similar theorems are valid for vector spaces, modules, and rings. \nIt dates back to the work of Richard Dedekind, and was further formalized by Emmy Noether into the isomorphism theorems. \nGroup-theoretic version.\nGiven two groups formula_1 and formula_2 and a group homomorphism formula_3, let formula_4 be a normal subgroup in formula_1 and formula_6 the natural surjective homomorphism formula_7 (where formula_8 is the quotient group of formula_1 by formula_4). If formula_4 is a subset of formula_12 (where formula_13 represents a kernel) then there exists a unique homomorphism formula_14 such that formula_15.\nIn other words, the natural projection formula_6 is universal among homomorphisms on formula_1 that map formula_4 to the identity element.\nThe situation is described by the following commutative diagram:\nformula_19 is injective if and only if formula_20. Therefore, by setting formula_20, we immediately get the first isomorphism theorem.\nWe can write the statement of the fundamental theorem on homomorphisms of groups as \"every homomorphic image of a group is isomorphic to a quotient group\".\nProof.\nThe proof follows from two basic facts about homomorphisms, namely their preservation of the group operation, and their mapping of the identity element to the identity element. We need to show that if formula_22 is a homomorphism of groups, then: \nProof of 1.\nThe operation tha