{"id": "11615", "revid": "11308236", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=11615", "title": "Finite field", "text": "Algebraic structure\nIn mathematics, a finite field or Galois field (so-named in honor of \u00c9variste Galois) is a field that has a finite number of elements. As with any field, a finite field is a set on which the operations of multiplication, addition, subtraction and division are defined and satisfy certain basic rules. The most common examples of finite fields are the integers mod formula_1 when formula_1 is a prime number.\nThe \"order\" of a finite field is its number of elements, which is either a prime number or a prime power. For every prime number formula_1 and every positive integer formula_4 there are fields of order formula_5. All finite fields of a given order are isomorphic.\nFinite fields are fundamental in a number of areas of mathematics and computer science, including number theory, algebraic geometry, Galois theory, finite geometry, cryptography and coding theory.\nProperties.\nA finite field is a field that is a finite set; this means that it has a finite number of elements on which multiplication, addition, subtraction and division (excluding division by zero) are defined and satisfy the field axioms.\nThe number of elements of a finite field is called its \"order\" or, sometimes, its \"size\". A finite field of order formula_6 exists if and only if formula_6 is a prime power formula_5 (where formula_1 is a prime number and formula_4 is a positive integer). In a field of order formula_5, adding formula_1 copies of any element always results in zero; that is, the characteristic of the field is formula_1.\nFor formula_14, all fields of order formula_6 are isomorphic (see \"\" below). Moreover, a field cannot contain two different finite subfields with the same order. One may therefore identify all finite fields with the same order, and they are unambiguously denoted formula_16, formula_17 or formula_18, where the letters GF stand for \"Galois field\".\nIn a finite field of order formula_6, the polynomial formula_20 has all formula_6 elements of the finite field as roots. The non-zero elements of a finite field form a multiplicative group. This group is cyclic, so all non-zero elements can be expressed as powers of a single element called a primitive element of the field. (In general there will be several primitive elements for a given field.)\nThe simplest examples of finite fields are the fields of prime order: for each prime number formula_1, the prime field of order formula_1 may be constructed as the integers modulo formula_1, formula_25.\nThe elements of the prime field of order formula_1 may be represented by integers in the range formula_27. The sum, the difference and the product are the remainder of the division by formula_1 of the result of the corresponding integer operation. The multiplicative inverse of an element may be computed by using the extended Euclidean algorithm (see \"\").\nLet formula_29 be a finite field. For any element formula_30 in formula_29 and any integer formula_32, denote by formula_33 the sum of formula_32 copies of formula_30. The least positive formula_32 such that formula_37 is the characteristic formula_1 of the field. This allows defining a multiplication formula_39 of an element formula_4 of formula_41 by an element formula_30 of formula_29 by choosing an integer representative for formula_4. This multiplication makes formula_29 into a formula_41-vector space. It follows that the number of elements of formula_29 is formula_48 for some integer formula_32.\nThe identity\nformula_50\n(sometimes called the freshman's dream) is true in a field of characteristic formula_1. This follows from the binomial theorem, as each binomial coefficient of the expansion of formula_52, except the first and the last, is a multiple of formula_1.\nBy Fermat's little theorem, if formula_1 is a prime number and formula_30 is in the field formula_41 then formula_57. This implies the equality\nformula_58\nfor polynomials over formula_41. More generally, every element in formula_60 satisfies the polynomial equation formula_61.\nAny finite field extension of a finite field is separable and simple. That is, if formula_62 is a finite field and formula_29 is a subfield of formula_62, then formula_62 is obtained from formula_29 by adjoining a single element whose minimal polynomial is separable. To use a piece of jargon, finite fields are perfect.\nA more general algebraic structure that satisfies all the other axioms of a field, but whose multiplication is not required to be commutative, is called a division ring (or sometimes \"skew field\"). By Wedderburn's little theorem, any finite division ring is commutative, and hence is a finite field.\nExistence and uniqueness.\nLet formula_67 be a prime power, and formula_29 be the splitting field of the polynomial \nformula_69\nover the prime field formula_41. This means that formula_29 is a finite field of lowest order, in which formula_72 has formula_6 distinct roots (the formal derivative of formula_72 is formula_75, implying that formula_76, which in general implies that the splitting field is a separable extension of the original). The above identity shows that the sum and the product of two roots of formula_72 are roots of formula_72, as well as the multiplicative inverse of a root of formula_72. In other words, the roots of formula_72 form a field of order formula_6, which is equal to formula_29 by the minimality of the splitting field.\nThe uniqueness up to isomorphism of splitting fields implies thus that all fields of order formula_6 are isomorphic. Also, if a field formula_29 has a field of order formula_14 as a subfield, its elements are the formula_6 roots of formula_20, and formula_29 cannot contain another subfield of order formula_6.\nIn summary, we have the following classification theorem first proved in 1893 by E.\u00a0H.\u00a0Moore:\nThe order of a finite field is a prime p